      <title type="html"><![CDATA[A Quick Markdown Syntax Error Detection for Writing MathJax Equations in Octopress Posts (1)]]></title>
      <link href="https://vincenttam.github.io/blog/2014/12/10/a-quick-markdown-syntax-error-detection-for-writing-mathjax-equations-in-octopress-posts-1/"/>
    
    <updated>2014-12-10T14:57:23+08:00</updated>
    <id>https://vincenttam.github.io/blog/2014/12/10/a-quick-markdown-syntax-error-detection-for-writing-mathjax-equations-in-octopress-posts-1</id>
    
      <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h2 id="backgroud">Backgroud</h2>

<p>I write math in <a href="http://octopress.org">Octopress</a> posts using <a href="http://www.mathjax.org">MathJax</a>.</p>

<h2 id="problems">Problems</h2>

<p>I include $\rm \LaTeX$ code for mathematical expressions rendered by
MathJax in Markdown source code for Octopress posts.  Then I have to
adapt the $\rm \LaTeX$ code for <a href="http://kramdown.gettalong.org">kramdown</a>, which is a Markdown parser
that converts kramdown code into HTML.  For example,</p>

<ol>
  <li>Add a backslash ‘\’ before an underscore <code>\_</code>.<sup id="fnref:underscore"><a href="#fn:underscore" class="footnote">1</a></sup></li>
  <li>Use <em>eight</em> backslashes to stand for a newline in displayed math
equations.<sup id="fnref:8backslash"><a href="#fn:8backslash" class="footnote">2</a></sup></li>
</ol>

<p>For the second item, I realized that by <em>repeated</em> trials.</p>

<p>Regeneration of the contents in this blog takes more than a minute
since <a href="http://jekyllrb.com">jekyll</a> needs to process more than 200 pages.  Therefore, a
<em>quicker</em> way to verify the Markdown syntax helps.</p>

<h2 id="method">Method</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Write the $\rm \LaTeX$ code for the equations.</li>
  <li>Use a $\rm \LaTeX$ compiler to ensure that the code for the
equations are right.</li>
  <li>Use <a href="http://johnmacfarlane.net/pandoc">pandoc</a> to convert the $\rm \LaTeX$ code to Markdown.</li>
  <li>Use kramdown to convert the Markdown (i.e. kramdown) code to HTML.</li>
  <li>Copy and paste the HTML code into the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> tag of an HTML file.</li>
  <li>Add references to MathJax and a local configuration file in the
<code>&lt;head&gt;</code> tag in the HTML file.</li>
  <li>Use a web browser to preview the results.</li>
  <li>Correct the Markdown syntax, and repeat steps 4–7 if necessary,
until the contents are correctly displayed.</li>
  <li>Copy the kramdown code and paste it under the YAML header in the
Markdown source file for an Octopress post.</li>
</ol>

<p>Therefore, I often excute the following editor commands in <a href="http://www.vim.org">Vim</a>.</p>

<pre class="cliUB"><code>:" returns the relative path of the file the current buffer
:echo expand('%')
:!kramdown % &gt; %&lt;.html
:sp %&lt;.html
</code></pre>

<hr />

<div class="footnotes">
  <ol>
    <li id="fn:underscore">

      <p>See <a href="http://www.lucypark.kr/blog/2013/02/25/mathjax-kramdown-and-octopress/index.html#escape-markdown-syntax"><em>Mathjax, Kramdown and Octopress</em></a> by Lucy Park. <a href="#fnref:underscore" class="reversefootnote">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:8backslash">

      <p>See <a href="/blog/2014/09/07/mathjax-and-rss/index.html#method"><em>MathJax and RSS</em></a> in Blog 1 for details. <a href="#fnref:8backslash" class="reversefootnote">&#8617;</a></p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</div>
]]></content>
    
